#Text=[ Laughs ]
#Text=And that 's where we fit in , now !
#Text=Freaks !
#Text=Sharin Foo : Sounds like an interesting job .
#Text=A lot of the questions might be a little different than what you are typically used to ; maybe that will make it more interesting for you , or less pleasant .
#Text=One of the first questions I like to ask musicians is about the challenge to be innovative when so much has already been done .
#Text=How do you not let that affect your output ?
#Text=Well , I do n't think we really think about it in those terms .
#Text=When we started out we had certain guidelines for the music that would ensure that it would sound like no one else , and those were pretty easy to make .
#Text=Things like do n't use a high hat , do n't use cymbals , do n't use certain things , play all the songs in the same key , do this and this , and that was really ...
#Text=Was that your Dogme influence ?
#Text=Yeah .
#Text=I do n't know what it was , I guess it was a really silly thing , but it worked and it was very inspiring and creative to work within those constraints , I guess .
#Text=But they were n't really constrains for us , it was actually really easy and simple , but I think it has a sound that I have never heard before .
#Text=But like I said , I do n't really thin that we think ...
#Text=I think it 's more that we are not scared of being blunt about what the references are in our music .
#Text=For instance , if you look at our name , The Raveonettes , it 's a complete direct reference to The Ronettes and Buddy Holly Rave On .
#Text=So , in that sense , we 're pretty clear about it .
#Text=You embrace it .
#Text=Yeah , we like it .
#Text=Yeah , where the inspiration has come from .
#Text=So it 's not like we have that fear of repetition .
#Text=I think a lot of bands put a lot of emphasis on trying to be different , and then they make music that is soulless ; it does n't get me anywhere .
#Text=It 's too self-aware ?
#Text=Yeah , what 's wrong with the three chords ?
#Text=That 's what music was founded upon , that 's what everyone from Hank Williams to The Ramones used those three chords .
#Text=What 's wrong with them all of a sudden ?
#Text=Yes .
#Text=I think that what it comes down to is whether it strikes a chord in you and hits your gut , some kind of emotion in you , that 's really what we care about when we make music .
#Text=Since you are so upfront about your influences , you do still have unique sound .
#Text=Do the constant comparison in the music media grow tiresome ?
